🚀 Building Ultra-Low Latency REST Applications in Modern C++: An In-Depth Look at the CETAN Server Platform
When building backend microservices, developers often default to stacks like Go, Node.js, or Rust. However, when ultra-low latency, granular memory control, and minimal runtime overhead are non-negotiable requirements, modern C++ remains unparalleled.
The challenge? Creating high-performance REST applications in C++ typically requires stitching together an uncohesive web of third-party routing libraries, configuration parsers, and security frameworks.
To solve this, we spent the last few years developing and refining CETAN: a dedicated, native C++ web application server built specifically for the modern Linux ecosystem. Whether you are hosting dynamic C++ services alongside static web assets or spinning up highly isolated containers, CETAN provides a unified, production-ready runtime environment.
🛠️ The Core Architecture & Requirements
We engineered CETAN from the ground up utilizing modern C++23, allowing us to leverage the latest language efficiencies and compiler optimizations.

• Runtime Target: CETAN is a Linux-first platform targeting modern runtimes (requiring GLIBC++ ≥ GLIBCXX_3.4.33 and a C++23 toolchain like g++ 14).

• Declarative Configuration: Rather than hardcoding structural parameters into your binaries, applications are easily configured using a centralized, standard XML file (cetan_config.xml).

• Deployment Flexibility: The entire system is micro-container ready, offering full compatibility with bare-metal Linux deployments as well as pre-built Docker infrastructure.
⚡ Benchmark Performance (Testing on a Baseline Machine)
Instead of renting a massive, multi-core cloud instance to yield artificial performance numbers, we wanted to see how CETAN’s dynamic routing engine handled sustained, high-concurrency pressure on modest, legacy consumer desktop hardware.
We ran a rigorous 30-second sustained load test against a dynamic /ping endpoint hosted directly at the application root to force full-depth routing lookups.

• Test Hardware: Intel Core i5 (4th Generation), 4 Cores, 16GB RAM

• Test Utility: wrk -t8 -c400 -d30s https://cetan.io

• Test Isolation: The integrated Web Guard AI component was disabled during this run to establish a true framework baseline.
The Results:

• Throughput: 31,071.93 Requests/sec

• Data Transfer Rate: 3.76 MB/sec

• Average Latency: 12.88 ms (Stdev: 3.37 ms, Max: 132.66 ms)
Because this test was conducted on hardware that is roughly a decade old, throughput metrics and processing latency scale exponentially higher when deploying CETAN to modern server-grade CPUs.
🧠 Intrinsic AI Security: Introducing Web Guard
One of the most distinctive aspects of CETAN is its native security boundary. Instead of routing all your inbound web traffic through heavy, resource-intensive external Web Application Firewalls (WAFs), CETAN features an integrated subsystem called CETAN AI — Web Guard.
Web Guard deploys a highly optimized, low-latency transformer model that inspects incoming HTTP requests directly inside the server pipeline. By analyzing traffic footprints in real-time, it seamlessly classifies requests as normal, suspicious, or malicious. This catches automation frameworks, fuzzers, and scanning tools (like sqlmap or wpscan) before they ever touch your actual application endpoints.
💻 Implementation: A Simple REST Endpoint
Writing a RESTful microservice inside the CETAN ecosystem is straightforward. The framework handles the boilerplate, allowing you to map explicit resources to clean handlers:
// Greeting service mapped to /rest-101/greeting/hello-world
class Greeting : public WebService {
public:
Greeting() : WebService("/greeting") {}
Response hello_world() {
Response resp(200);
resp.body("<html>Hello, World!</html>");
return resp;
}
private:
std::vector<Resource*> register_resources() const override {
std::vector<Resource*> resources;
resources.emplace_back(new Resource("GET", "/hello-world", &Greeting::hello_world));
return resources;
}
};🔒 Enterprise Features, Built-In
Rather than bloating your codebase with fragments of third-party software, CETAN bundles structural web development requirements directly into the SDK:

• Thread-Safe Logging (SLog): High-throughput backends require zero-blocking tracking. Our native SLog logging subsystem offers thread-safe, lightning-fast structured tracking directly out of the box.

• Integrated JSON Handling: Modern data interchange demands native serialization. CETAN includes its own compiled JSON & XML RESTful parsing stack optimized directly for C++23.

• Encrypted Secrets Management: Hardcoding private tokens, database keys, or API credentials into code or clear-text configurations is an extreme security risk. We built a companion utility named Safe that writes encrypted .safe archives. You simply reference the safe key inside your server configuration, keeping secrets locked at rest.

• Protocol-Level Security: Features immediate native support for TLS/HTTPS encryption, granular IP filtering (via CIDR whitelists/blacklists), and automated Bearer, Basic, or LDAP authentication.
